 Sustainable genuineness in the fashion industry 

 Upcycling is the future of fashion. Upcycling is the act of taking something no longer in use and giving it a second life and new function. This can help solve the overproduction if everybody would upcycle their old clothes we would have to buy much less. Because of the overproduction, globally 4 billion pounds of clothes are put in landfills. This is a massive waste and, not all clothes are biodegradable. Upcycling can help to solve this, but upcycling is not easy. Lots of brands try to upcycle. Now, it has become a trend so, when is upcycling done out of good intentions? 

 

There are many brands that try upcycling, but they all try in different ways. 
 I looked into how high-end brands implemented upcycling. 
Vogue wrote an article about how upcycling is a trend right now. Balenciaga made a shaggy coat out of shoelace fur as you can see in the picture.  I am a bit worried about how the article writes about upcycling being a trend. Trends are good in the way that they create attention for a certain topic. However, trends are known to fly over and can cause insincerity.  

Balenciaga is new to upcycling and selling non-sustainable clothes. The Balenciaga collection that was mentioned in the vogue article was the ss2021. 93,5% of the plain materials of this collection are either certified sustainable or upcycled. In their Fall 2021 collection, they also used a lot of certified or recycled materials, I couldnt find any numbers. Whereas their 2022 collections dont include certified and recycled materials, or it is not mentioned. This causes me to be sceptical about their intentions 

They also communicated that they intended their ss2021 collection to be unisex. In my opinion, Balenciaga does a great job in inclusivity. Another example is their fall 2021 collection this collection has some garments included with gay pride on them. Balenciaga continuously shows their inclusivity, in my eyes. 

 

In a way to look at more haute culture houses, I researched the mother company of Balenciaga Kering. 
Kering mentions on their website that they choose 3 aspects to develop a more sustainable and responsible luxury brand. These 3 aspects are care, collaborate and create. Subjectively, I wasnt blown away by this aspect because they are undetailed and common. However, when I read their plans in more detail these words meant more. On their website, they clearly show their target and what they already have achieved. For example, they want to reduce their footprint by 40 percent by 2025. Now they achieved a 14 percent reduction, which is in a good direction. To be sceptical it is hard to find how they achieved this goal. They do show the sustainability materials they use and why by using sustainable materials they would reduce their footprint. I think there is another step in the value chain that they changed. Because to percentages they achieved requires lots of sustainable changes. Kering has a lot of information about their sustainability on their website about c02 emissions, circularity, innovation labs, and upcycling. One of Kerings many collaborations is with La Rserve des Art, they collect scraps and materials. Kering uses these materials for upcycling.  

In 2021 SG analytics came out with a top 10 most sustainable companies, where Kering is on 7. So, I think that proves the impact Kering has. 

 

In short, genuineness is hard to prove. It is easy to always drought or be sceptical. I think its trust you can have in a brand. To go back to the Balenciaga example, subjectively I am not convinced that they upcycled because they honestly wanted to. I have this opinion because their latest collections are not sustainable, as far as I know. I think Karin rather wanted Balenciaga to do an upcycled collection, then that they came up with the idea. But that is my opinion and not per se the truth. However, sometimes it does not matter if its genuine or not, they do something good. That doesnt make everything they do good or trustworthy, but it makes an impact.

The world faces a global climate crisis. 

Extreme overconsumption and overproduction are the responsible factors for a world that is almost burned out of resources. Change is no longer an opportunity and more of an obligation for all of us.

The fashion industry is next to the oil industry the worldwide second largest polluting factor.

Fashion as a commodity? Sounds harsh and exaggerated but over the last years, this attitude became a sad reality. Each year we sort out over one billion garments - and this only in Germany. That means each person throws away around thirty-five pieces annually. A shocking fact that points out the problem we are facing. Tremendous amounts of valuable and scarce resources get wasted for the worldwide clothing production with the result of us giving them away after wearing a piece maybe once.

Not only a reduced consumption is necessary we also need a new economic system that works to protect the last resources on the planet.


A full circular economy could be a solution for this. Old materials have to be brought back into our economic circle to prevent that we are draining in our rubbish. Facing the fashion industry the idea of up-cycling can work against massive textile waste. By using what is already been made instead of producing new we can break through old patterns.


What exactly is up-cycling?


Upcycling is now very popular, especially in the fashion sector, as there are hardly any limits to creativity. Clothing can be enlarged, reduced, repaired, customized, or repurposed.

Rubbish is avoided because the garments have a second or third life. In addition, resources are conserved, which is important to protect the planet. So up-cycling is an absolute counter-trend to fast fashion.

Comparing the usual garment production to the up-cycling process it can be said that transport routes are radically shortened. An item is often shipped around the whole world till it ends up in our wardrobes. Up-cycling combined with using local resources can improve the footprint of a garment remarkable.


Where does up-cycling come from and how does it work?


The term up-cycling dates back to 1994 and was invented by the engineer Reiner Pilz. He expressed criticism of the previous recycling process, in which the quality of the recycled products is lower than the quality of the raw materials. The used materials should be upgraded and are supposed to have a higher quality according to the up-cycling process. During processing, the focus is on using a few new resources. The main advantage is that the process is more sustainable and also that you can create unique pieces



A great role model is the British designer Christopher Raeburn. His store concept is based on the three Rs - Remade, Recycle, and Reuse. In his studio in east London, he designs unique pieces out of used textiles and connects them in new shapes, forms, and innovative solutions. As an example Raeburn up-cycles military capes and trousers out of parachutes. They not only look appealing, but the material is also resistant what guarantees a long-living garment.

His work is an inspiring example to show how up-cycling can be a sustainable, fashionable as well as a successful model.

- Antonia Ochs

How have the goths and minimalists influenced our society?

 

As humans, we form ourselves into groups with similarities or interests; why? Well, mainly safety and inclusivity. We do this to create comfort in our lives, feel included, and ignore the mass of the world and how we are just 1 of many. Over time and in different languages, this behaviour started to appear throughout our history as the term of subcultures, with it being established officially are the early 1900s. In different fields, the definition of the term can change. However, in general terms, subcultures are generally groups that are perceived to deviate from the normative standards of the dominant culture (Amy Herzog, 1999) from goths to the minimalists. Over our history, different subcultures have appeared, evolved, and dissolved as time goes on.

 

So how have the goths and minimalists influenced our society? As with many subcultures, it is nearly impossible to see how all have changed our society for good or bad. However, let us look at the goths and the minimalists. These two can be seen as examples of different ways of living and their implications on how they have affected society throughout history. 

 

The semi-nomadic populations, the people known as goths (visigoths and the ostrogoths), are the first to fall within the name of goths. Their implication on society is straightforward, with them capturing and disposing of ancient rome and the disposal of the western empire. The gothic subculture, after its creations, developed even more. In the renaissance period, it was used in literature. the famous giorgio vassari, in his book lives of the artists was the first to use the terminology in a derogative  (A brief history of goths, 2017) way to describe the past medieval times and its art and architecture like the abbey of saint-denis as gothic, referring to the lifestyle of the past barbaric semi-nomadic people. The modern-day gothic subculture is a class that represents the ever-changing and treatment of others. The subcultural society remains a robust underground phenomenon of fashion and music. Their inspiration of the 70s post-punk music groups, lyrical gloominess, horror and dark clothing, develops the historical figure of gothic culture. The subculture of being an outcast, the rebellious and unconfirmed people, is all goths connections; they are unwelcoming throughout history. Although being a part of any subculture is different from mainstream society. Certain groups like the goths are excluded more today and in the past. This contributes to the constant conflict we have and will continue to have.

 

Minimalism is another subculture of today; this subculture represents nearly every aspect of society, from fashion to how we live and what we surround ourselves with daily. Its likeability says that minimalism has become a trendy and influential subculture, but it allows for interoperation. Its interpretive trait is evident in minimal streetwear. Typical, it uses neutral tones and requires block colours, having only a couple of layers of clothing. However, minimal fashion does not have any set rules; therefore, wearing a monochrome outfit can be considered minimal, or some patterned clothing is considered minimal. The minimalist fashion style allows people to be free and be themselves. A minimalist has the idea of having a need and only using and wasting as little as possible. Typically, it is clean, and like in fashion, it follows a neutral tone to create a calming atmospheric living space. It is a way of looking at the world to create change for many people. It became popular because of its help in trying to end overconsumption. People like Marie kondo (konmari) and her netflix series and cleaning index; although she says she is not a minimalist (Kondo, 2021) , she has contributed to helping people be cleaner and own what they love. An ideology that the minimalist lifestyle follows.

 

So, to answer how have goths and minimalists influenced our society, it is simple, they do. Nearly every aspect of this subculture and others affects our society; after all, they are cultures. Whether it is war, art movements, literature, a group of young people in an underground club, or a simplistic and stable lifestyle, subcultures create the time to talk and communicate about problems. They allow people to express themself and fight for whom they want to be, which i believe is a core value for the future. The goths and the minimalists are just two examples of how subcultures thrived and survived throughout history. Their travels of reaching different parts of the world contribute to society. In the end, we can say that everyone is different, so really, what is the difference? Well, it is the outcome. Just these two alone, over time, became so large that now people are influenced to pick what they like and dislike; therefore, there is this sense of every subculture around the world. This influence is what i believe in creating a coherent world.

- Arryn Ward
